Project Description

Now that you’ve learned about basic data manipulation in R, it’s time to learn how to input a data file into R and learn the concept of data frame.

Learn how to read various data files, such as text, CSV, and Excel.

Refer to the Data Camp tutorial. You can always get help for a command by typing ?[command] (eg: ?read.csv) in the RStudio Console

  1. Load the FaceBook datasets provided into data frames, and compare reading different file types by creating 3 data frames for each file type.
# Solution from StackOverflow:
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1523126/how-to-read-data-when-some-numbers-contain-commas-as-thousand-separator

setClass("num.with.commas")
setAs("character", "num.with.commas", 
        function(from) as.numeric(gsub(",", "", from) ) )
df_text <- read.table("Facebook Friends.txt", skip = 1, header = TRUE, sep = '\t', 
                      skipNul = TRUE, colClasses=c('num.with.commas'))
## Warning in readLines(file, skip): line 1 appears to contain an embedded nul
df_text
df_csv <- read.csv("Facebook Friends.csv", skip = 1, header = TRUE, sep = "\t",
                   colClasses=c('num.with.commas'))
df_csv
df_xls <- readWorksheetFromFile("Facebook Friends.xlsx", sheet = 1, startRow = 3)
df_xls

  1. For the data frame above, use the names function to show the column names. Notice column called “X..of.Tags”. The column from the raw file is actually “# of Tags”. R converted this due to spaces. Rename this column to “Tags” using base R. (see: the Cookbook resource in supplementals).
names(df_csv)
##  [1] "Friend"       "Age"          "Photos"       "X..of.Tags"   "Albums"      
##  [6] "Gender"       "Emp"          "Profile"      "Cover"        "Orientation"

# Note: I noticed a few columns were "factors".  It turned out that these had "thousands" numbers with commas in them.  I did some reasearch and changed the way that i did the import, fixing this on the import vs. here.
  1. Create a data frame from the CSV data frame, using subset that includes 3 fields: Gender, Posts, Friends. Include only valid Gender values (Male=1; Female=0). Use head to display the top records. (see: Quick-R: Data Management)
df1 <- subset(df_csv, Gender == 0 | Gender == 1, select=c('Gender','Posts', 'Friends'))
head(df1)
# One Last change - Make the Gender a Factor
df1$Gender <- as.factor(df1$Gender)
df1
  1. We will use this dataset to do data visualization in the next session. But you can start practicing a variety of data visualization appropriate for this dataset, such as histograms, pie charts, etc…

Create a couple of graphs of your choice.(see: Quick R: Graphics)

ggplot(data = df1, mapping = aes(x = Posts, y = Friends, color = Gender)) + 
  geom_point(position = "jitter") +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
